Name: Makenna Martin
comments: The instructions were easy to understand. My strategy for making decisions was more based on luck in the first half of the box picking, and then was based on maximizing money in the second half of the box picking. When doing this experiment I thought of casinos and how a lot of that is random until you "get lucky," because the box choosing was based on a computer randomly picking your box. I guess if I had taken statistics and weighed my options more, I could have done better in getting a higher amount. For the word problem portion, I tried to think of it as a math test and what strategies would work best. The problems were relatively simple, but (speaking as a college student) sometimes the most simple things are more difficult as we tend to overthink things. I definitely overthought some of the more simple math problems, even though they were not that challenging content wise.

Name: Gina Pletschet
comments: I was unsure during the first set of examples at the beginning how many boxes were being chosen out of a set. It became apparent later that it would be one. I was also unsure during the first example questions if the money meant exactly that amount or at least that amount ie if it is possible to get $8 is it true that it is also equally likely to get $6 because you are getting at least that much. My strategy was not much of a strategy. I am not very good at math. I haven't taken a math course in over 4 years and cannot do even basic math in my head as I am a music composition student and that is not part of our degree. I attempted to average things but I do not know if I did it correctly. It was mostly based off how much I was willing to lose or what the opportunity cost would be.
